in Juvenal: Nor do I, indeed, conceive the good Purposes served by inserting Characters of such angelic Perfection, or such diabolical Depravity, in any Work of Invention: Since from contemplating either, the Mind of Man is more likely to be overwhelmed with Sorrow and Shame, than to draw any good Uses from such Patterns; for in the former Instance the Mind of Man may be both concerned and ashamed to see a Pattern of Excellence, in the Mind of Man Nature, which the Mind of Man may reasonably despair of ever arriving at; and in contemplating the latter, the Mind of Man may be no less affected with those uneasy Sensations, at seeing the Nature, of which the Mind of Man is a Partaker, degraded into so odious and detestable a Creature.
